{{Featured list}}
[[File:Alastair-sim-laird-in-geordie.jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|right|Sim as the Laird in ''[[Geordie (film)|Geordie]]'', 1955]]
The Scottish actor [[Alastair Sim]] (1900–1976) performed in many mediums of [[light entertainment]], including theatre, film and television.<ref name="Times: Obit" /> His career spanned from 1930 until his death. During that time he was a "memorable character player of faded Anglo-Scottish gentility, whimsically put-upon countenance, and sepulchral, sometimes minatory, laugh".<ref name="BFI: Screenonline" />

After studying chemistry at the [[University of Edinburgh]], he was employed, between 1925 and 1930, as a lecturer in elocution at [[New College, Edinburgh]], and also established his own school of drama and speech training.{{sfn|Gilbert|2010}} In 1930 he made his professional stage debut as a messenger in ''[[Othello]]'' at the [[Savoy Theatre]], London{{sfn|Simpson|2009|p=38}}—with [[Paul Robeson]] and [[Peggy Ashcroft]] in the lead roles.{{sfn|Gilbert|2010}} During the next five years he appeared on stage in New York and the UK, and spent two years at the [[Old Vic]].{{sfn|Herbert|1978|p=1128}}

In 1935 he made his film debut, appearing in ''[[The Riverside Murder]]'' (dir. [[Albert Parker (director)|Albert Parker]]); he appeared in four films that year, and five the following.{{sfn|Simpson|2009|pp=193–197}} His film career progressed and by the mid 1940s he was a well-known figure in the theatre and cinema.<ref name="BFI: Screenonline" /> ''[[The Times]]'' highlighted some of his more notable films, including ''[[Green for Danger (film)|Green for Danger]]'' (1946), ''[[The Happiest Days of Your Life]]'' (1950), ''[[Scrooge (1951 film)|Scrooge]]'' (1951), ''[[An Inspector Calls (1954 film)|An Inspector Calls]]'' (1954), ''[[The Green Man (film)|The Green Man]]'' (1956) and ''[[School for Scoundrels (1960 film)|School for Scoundrels]]'' (1960).<ref name="Times: Obit" />

Sim had been [[Rector of the University of Edinburgh]] in 1951, and was awarded [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] in 1953, although he turned down a [[Knight Bachelor|knighthood]] that was offered to him by [[Edward Heath]].{{sfn|Gilbert|2010}} His biographer, Bruce Babington, considered that "Sim was the paradigm&nbsp;– authority figure, yes, but often shadily duplicitous, often a manipulator of official rhetoric, his sexless bachelor persona containing strains of sexual ambiguity, his jolliness a latent vampirism."<ref name="BFI: Screenonline" /> Sim died in August 1976.{{sfn|Gilbert|2010}}

