{{Infobox office holder | name = Göran Gentele | birth_name = | birth_date = 29 September 1917 | birth_place = [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]] | death_date = 18 July 1972 (aged 54)<ref>{{cite news |title= Gentele, Head of Met, Dies With 2 Children in Crash; Was Bing's Successor -Wife and 3d Daughter Injured in Sardinia Goeran Gentele, Director of Met, Dies in Auto Crash |url= https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1972/07/19/80797077.pdf}}</ref> | death_place = [[Olbia]], [[Sardegna]], [[Italy]] | image = Image:Ingarö kyrka Göran Gentele.jpg | occupation = Opera impresario |education = | spouse = | order = | office =[[Metropolitan Opera|General Manager of the Metropolitan Opera]] | term_start =1972| term_end =1972| appointed = | predecessor =[[Rudolf Bing]] | successor = }} '''Göran Gentele''' (29 September 1917 &ndash; 18 July 1972) was a [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[actor]], [[Film director|director]], and [[opera]] manager. He was briefly the general manager of the [[Metropolitan Opera]] in New York City in 1972.<ref name=time>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=New Manager for the Met |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,904611,00.html |quote=Rudolf Bing last week introduced the man who will succeed him two seasons hence as general manager of Manhattan's Metropolitan Opera. He is Sweden's Goran Gentele (pronounced Joran Gften-tell-uh), 53, who for the past seven years has directed the Royal Opera House in Stockholm. ... |work=[[Time magazine]] |date=December 21, 1970 |accessdate=2015-08-12 }}</ref>
==Biography== Born in [[Stockholm]], Gentele studied from 1944 until 1946 at the ''[[Dramatens elevskola]]'', beginning a brief career as a [[film]] [[actor]] not long afterwards. He soon turned to directing, working for a time at the [[Royal Dramatic Theatre]] and then at the [[Royal Swedish Opera]], where his more notable productions included [[Gian Carlo Menotti]]'s ''[[The Consul]]'' and [[Karl-Birger Blomdahl]]'s ''[[Aniara (opera)|Aniara]]''. He became director of the company in 1963.
He also directed films during approximately the same period (1947 to 1969), making at least 15 feature films and television movies. His 1951 film ''[[Leva på 'Hoppet']]'' was awarded the Silver Bear for comedy at the [[1st Berlin International Film Festival|Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref>IMDB: [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0313022/?ref_=nmbio_bio_nm Filmography], Accessed April 29, 2016</ref>
He succeeded Sir [[Rudolf Bing]] as director of the [[Metropolitan Opera]] in [[New York City]] in 1972.<ref name=time/> Soon after assuming the post, on 18 July 1972, Gentele died in an [[car crash|automobile accident]] while on vacation in [[Sardinia]]; he was killed along with two of his daughters when the car in which they were riding [[head-on collision|collided head-on]] with a truck. A third daughter was injured, as was Gentele's wife, Marit. [[Schuyler Chapin]], Gentele's assistant, was named acting director almost at once.
==Legacy== Despite the fact that he had been in office only a few weeks at his death, several of Gentele's plans for the company were implemented under Chapin. The most notable of these was a new production of [[Georges Bizet]]'s ''[[Carmen]]'' designed for [[Marilyn Horne]]; this was used to open the 1972-1973 season. Gentele was the second general director of the Metropolitan, behind [[Herbert Witherspoon]], to die before the opening night of his first season with the company.
==Awards== Gentele won the [[Silver Bear|Silver Bear (Comedies)]] award at the [[1st Berlin International Film Festival]] for his film ''[[Leva på 'Hoppet']]''.<ref name="Berlinale 1951">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1951/03_preistr_ger_1951/03_Preistraeger_1951.html |title=1st Berlin International Film Festival: Prize Winners |accessdate=2009-12-20 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref>
