'''José Thenèe''' was a world-renowned [[ironworker]] from [[Argentina]] in the 1920s and 1930s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.entrepreneur.com/magazine/entrepreneursstartupsmagazine/2009/march/200608.html|title=Design Your Office Space|last=Meyers|first=Tiffany|date=March 2009|work=[[Entrepreneur (magazine)|Entrepreneur]]|accessdate=30 October 2010}}</ref> He was commissioned by the government for special architectural projects, including the gate at the [[Technical Museum of Buenos Aires]]. He was named the [[National Ironworker of Argentina]] in 1929. One of his early chandeliers was bought by Insurance tycoon [[Richard Parrillo]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-176704777.html|title=At Burling mansion, even gravel is French. (Business of Life)|last=Kapos|first=Shia|date=March 10, 2008|work=[[Crain Communications|Crain's Chicago Business]]|publisher=HighBeam Research|accessdate=30 October 2010}}</ref> and resides in Parrillo's $40 million home in Chicago's [[Lincoln Park, Chicago|Lincoln Park]] neighborhood. His works command a high price.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articulo.mercadolibre.com.ar/MLA-93871360-arana-en-hierro-forjado-_JM|title=Araña en hierro forjado - $ 9000.00 en MercadoLibre|work=[[MercadoLibre.com]]|accessdate=30 October 2010|language=Spanish}}</ref>

