{{Korean people}}
{{Culture of Korea}}

'''Koreans''' ({{Korean|hangul=한민족|hanja=韓民族|rr=Hanminjok}} in [[South Korean standard language|South Korean]]; alternatively {{Korean|hangul=조선민족, 조선사람, 조선인|hanja=朝鮮民族, 朝鮮사람, 朝鮮人|rr=Joseonminjok, Joseonsaram, Joseonin|context=north}} in [[North Korean standard language|North Korean]], {{Literal translation|"Korean [[Korean ethnic nationalism|race]]"}}; see [[names of Korea]]) are an [[East Asian people|East Asian]] [[ethnic group]] originating from and native to [[Korea]] and southern [[Manchuria]].<ref>{{cite journal |author1= Wang, Yuchen|author2= Lu Dongsheng |author3= Chung Yeun-Jun |author4= Xu Shuhua |title=Genetic structure, divergence and admixture of Han Chinese, Japanese and Korean populations|journal= Hereditas |volume= 155 |pages= 19 |year=2018 |url=https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1186%2Fs41065-018-0057-5.pdf|doi= 10.1186/s41065-018-0057-5 |pmid= 29636655 |pmc= 5889524 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Wang |first=Yuchen  |last2= Lu |first2=Dongsheng |last3=Chung |first3=Yeun-Jun  |last4=Xu |first4=Shuhua |title=Genetic structure, divergence and admixture of Han Chinese, Japanese and Korean populations |url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s41065-018-0057-5 |journal=Hereditas |volume=155  |pages=19  |publication-date=April 6, 2018|doi=10.1186/s41065-018-0057-5  |pmid=29636655  |pmc=5889524  |year=2018  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s2EVi-MpnUsC&pg=PA6&dq=korean+origin+manchuria&hl=en&sa=X&ei=yuZdUan1PMLE4APmkoDQDw&ved=0CGAQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=korean+origin+manchuria&f=false|title=A History of Korea: From "Land of the Morning Calm" to States in Conflict|first=Jinwung|last=Kim|date=22 March 2018|publisher=Indiana University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Making of International Law in Korea: From Colony to Asian Power|last=Lee|first=Seokwoo|year=2016|isbn=978-9004315785|page=321}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Ethnicity and Foreigners in Ancient Greece and China|last=Kim|first=Hyunjin|publisher=Bloomsbury Academic|publication-date=21 May 2009|page=140}}</ref>

Koreans mainly live in the two Korean [[nation state]]s, [[South Korea]] and [[North Korea]] (collectively referred to simply as [[Korea]]), but are also an officially recognized ethnic minority in [[Koreans in China|China]], [[Koreans in Vietnam|Vietnam]], [[Koreans in Japan|Japan]] and [[Koreans in the Philippines|Philippines]], plus a number of former [[USSR|Soviet states]], such as [[Koreans in Russia|Russia]] and [[Koreans in Uzbekistan|Uzbekistan]]. Over the course of the 20th century, significant Korean communities have emerged in [[Korean Australians|Australia]], [[Korean Canadians|Canada]], [[Korean Americans|United States]] and, to a lesser extent, other nations with a primarily immigrant background.

As of 2017, there were an estimated 7.4 million ethnic [[Korean diaspora|Korean]]<nowiki/>s residing outside the Korean Peninsula.<ref name="MOFA"/>

==Etymology==
{{see also|Names of Korea}}
[[South Korea]]ns refer to themselves as ''Hanguk-in'' ({{Korean|hangul=한국인|hanja=韓國人}}), or ''Hanguk-saram'' ({{Korean|hangul=한국 사람}}), both of which mean "Korean nation people." When referring to members of the Korean diaspora, Koreans often use the term ''Han-in'' ({{Korean|hangul=한인|hanja=韓人}}; literally "Korean people").

[[North Korea]]ns refer to themselves as ''Joseon-in'' ({{Korean|hangul=조선인|hanja=朝鮮人}}) or ''Joseon-saram'' ({{Korean|hangul=조선 사람}}), both of which literally mean "[[Joseon]] people". The term is derived from the [[Joseon dynasty]], a Korean kingdom founded by [[Yi Seonggye]] that lasted for approximately five centuries from 1392 to 1910. Using similar words, [[Koreans in China]] refer to themselves as '''Chaoxianzu''' ({{zh|c=朝鲜族}}) in Chinese or '''Joseonjok, Joseonsaram''' ({{korean|hangul=조선족, 조선사람}}) in Korean, which are [[cognate]]s that literally mean "Joseon [[ethnic group]]".<ref>{{Cite book |title=The Making of International Law in Korea: From Colony to Asian Power |last=Lee, |first=Seokwoo |year=2016 |isbn=978-9004315785 |page=321}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |title=Ethnicity and Foreigners in Ancient Greece and China |last=Kim |first=Hyunjin  |publisher=Bloomsbury Academic |publication-date=21 May 2009 |page=140}}</ref> [[Zainichi Koreans]] refer to themselves as '''Zainichi Chousenjin, Chousenjin''' ({{lang-ja|在日朝鮮人, 朝鮮人}}) in Japanese or '''Jaeil Joseonin, Joseonsaram, Joseonin''' ({{korean|hangul=재일조선인, 조선사람, 조선인}}) in Korean

In the chorus of [[Aegukga]], the national anthem of South Korea, the Koreans are referred to as ''Daehan-saram'' ({{Korean|hangul=대한사람}}).

Ethnic Koreans living in Russia and Central Asia refer to themselves as [[Koryo-saram]] ({{Korean|hangul=고려 사람}}; [[Cyrillic script]]: Корё сарам), alluding to [[Goryeo]], a Korean dynasty spanning from 918 to 1392.

==Origins==
===Linguistic and archaeological studies===
Koreans are the descendants or an admixture of the ancient people who settled in the Korean Peninsula, historically said to be Siberian<ref>{{cite book|last=Nelson|first=Sarah M.|title=The Archaeology of Korea}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://100.naver.com/100.nhn?docid=186719|script-title=ko:한민족|trans-title=Korean people|language=ko|encyclopedia=Doosan Encyclopædia|via=NAVER Corp.|accessdate=9 March 2007}}</ref> or paleo-Asian.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://preview.britannica.co.kr/bol/topic.asp?article_id=b24h2877b|script-title=ko:한민족|trans-title=Korean people|language=ko|encyclopedia=Encyclopædia Britannica Korea|accessdate=9 March 2007|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120801195956/http://preview.britannica.co.kr/bol/topic.asp?article_id=b24h2877b|archivedate=1 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Archaeological evidence suggests that proto-Koreans were migrants from [[Manchuria]] during the [[Liaoning bronze dagger culture|Bronze Age]].<ref name="Ahn2010">{{cite journal|last=Ahn|first=Sung-Mo|title=The emergence of rice agriculture in Korea: archaeobotanical perspectives|journal=Archaeological and Anthropological Sciences|volume=2|issue=2|date=June 2010|pages=89–98|issn=1866-9557|doi=10.1007/s12520-010-0029-9}}</ref> It is noteworthy to mention that there were already people<ref>Vovin, Alexander. 2008. "高句麗에서 耽羅까지ᅳ韓国祖語를 말한 騎馬人들과 함께 南쪽을 향하여 천천히 내려오면서ᅳ" ("From Koguryo to Tamna: Slowly Riding South with the Speakers of Proto-Korean"). Lecture at the Seoul National University on May 15, 2008. Travel fully funded by the Seoul National University.</ref> living on the Korean peninsula from the [[Jeulmun pottery period|Paleolithic age]] and [[Mumun pottery period|Neolithic age]], and thus it is logical to assume that there was intermingling between these populations.

Linguistic evidence indicates speakers of proto-Korean languages were established in southeastern Manchuria and northern Korean peninsula by the [[Three Kingdoms of Korea]] period, and migrated from there to southern Korea during this period.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Vovin, Alexander (2008). From Koguryo to Tamna: Slowly Riding to the South with Speakers of Proto-Korean|journal=Korean Linguistics|volume=15}}</ref>

The largest concentration of [[dolmen]]s in the world is found on the [[Korean Peninsula]]. In fact, with an estimated 35,000-100,000 dolmen,{{sfn|Nelson|1993|p=147}} Korea accounts for nearly 70% of the world's total. Similar dolmens can be found in [[Manchuria]], the [[Shandong Peninsula]] and the [[Kyushu]] island, yet it is unclear why this culture only flourished so extensively on the Korean Peninsula and its surroundings compared to the bigger remainder of Northeastern Asia.

